] = [1, 1 + 2 - 1], = [1, 2] = (1, 2) does not occur in nums.\nTherefore, nums is not consecutive.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [3,5,4]\nOutput: true\nExplanation:\nThe minimum value is 3 and the length of nums is 3.\nAll of the values in the range [x, x + n - 1] = [3, 3 + 3 - 1] = [3, 5] = (3, 4, 5) occur in nums.\nTherefore, nums is consecutive.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 105\n0 <= nums[i] <= 105\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def isConsecutive(self, nums: List[int]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def isConsecutive(self, nums: List[int]) -> bool:\n        min_num = min(nums)\n        n = len(nums)\n        expected_set = set(range(min_num, min_num + n))\n        return set(nums) == expected_set\n```\n\nThis solution works by first finding the minimum number in the list, `min_num`, and then creating a set of numbers that would be expected in a consecutive range starting from `min_num` with length `n`. It then checks if the set of `nums` is equal to this expected set. If they are equal, it means that `nums` contains every number in the range `[min_num, min_num + n - 1]`, and thus the function returns `True`. Otherwise, it returns `False`. This approach efficiently checks for consecutiveness in O(n) time complexity.", "estimated_date": 1648944000000}